diet-related constipation for many years. She has no other symptoms other than mild tenderness over the left lower quadrant. A plain X-ray is performed to determine if she is faecally loaded (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the radiological finding in the pelvis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcified fibroid","Bladder calculus","Faecolith","Pelvic vein phlebolith","Gallstone ileus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a large calcified mass in the pelvis. This is a completely incidental finding. \u003Cstrong\u003ECalcified leiomyomas\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common calcified solid masses in the female pelvis. Whilst it might represent be a bladder calculus several facts detract from this. Firstly, the irregular margins would be against this being a bladder stone, as would the fact that bladder stones are more commonly found in men with bladder outlet obstruction. In addition, a stone that size within the bladder would almost certainly produce symptoms. Pelvic vein phleboliths are very common calcifications in pelvic veins but would not reach this size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGallstone ileus is incorrect because of the morphology of the calcification and the fact that the radiograph does not show other features suggestive of small bowel ileus. In addition, patients with gallstone ileus will typically present with symptoms of small bowel obstruction. Faecoliths may occur at any site in the colon and can be found in the appendix. They are rarely calcified and if so, have a lamellated appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The incidental finding of a large, round calcified mass in a female pelvis will almost certainly be a calcified fibroid."],"references":["Zulfiqar M, Shetty A, Tsai R et al. Diagnostic Approach to Benign and Malignant Calcifications in the Abdomen and Pelvis RadioGraphics 2020; 40:731\u201353."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92104"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"857"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18649"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18649"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cde361b6-628e-430d-b42e-16ec6fe4e38a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cde361b6-628e-430d-b42e-16ec6fe4e38a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":360,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92104"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T07:09:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T07:09:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"857"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109707"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"dat